+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012GRMDjjZ3otF3nNG2pvbFD","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have full context. Let me compile the complete review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Bug Fixes for Event-Driven Order Processing System\n\n**Test Results**: All 34 tests pass across 5 test files.\n\nThe commit `353bfd3` fixes 6 deliberately planted bugs from commit `1498d76`. Below is a fix-by-fix analysis.\n\n---\n\n### Fix 1: EventBus -- Global Handler Registry to Instance-Level Handlers\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/events/bus.ts`\n\n**Bug**: The handler registry was a module-level `Map` (`globalHandlers`) shared across all `EventBus` instances. This meant separate `EventBus` instances (e.g., in parallel tests or independent subsystems) would leak handlers between each other, and `clear()` on one instance would wipe all instances' handlers.\n\n**Fix**: Moved the handlers `Map` to a private instance property (`this.handlers`).\n\n**Assessment**: **Correct and complete.** This is a textbook fix. Each `EventBus` instance now owns its own handler registry. The `clear()` method properly scopes to the instance. The test at `/workspace/tests/events.test.ts` (lines 42-50) validates that `clear()` works at the instance level.\n\n**No issues found.**\n\n---\n\n### Fix 2: BillingService -- Missing `.bind(this)` on Refund Handler\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/billing/service.ts`, line 25\n\n**Bug**: `this.handleRefund` was passed as a bare method reference without `.bind(this)`, meaning when invoked by the EventBus, `this` would be `undefined` (in strict mode) rather than the `BillingService` instance. This would cause `this.payments.get(...)` and `this.notificationService.sendRefundNotice(...)` to fail at runtime.\n\n**Fix**: Changed to `this.handleRefund.bind(this)`.\n\n**Assessment**: **Correct.** This matches the pattern already used on line 24 for `handleStockReserved`. The test at `/workspace/tests/billing.test.ts` (lines 101-126) validates that refunds work correctly through the event handler path.\n\n**No issues found.**\n\n---\n\n### Fix 3: Billing Calculator -- Double-Rounding and Missing Total Rounding\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/billing/calculator.ts`, lines 20-29\n\n**Bug**: Two problems in one. (a) Intermediate values (`discountAmount`, `afterDiscount`, `taxAmount`) were each individually rounded to 2 decimal places before being used in subsequent calculations, which introduced compounding rounding errors (the \"double-rounding\" problem). (b) The final `total` was NOT rounded, despite all other fields being rounded.\n\n**Fix**: Removed intermediate rounding -- `discountAmount`, `afterDiscount`, and `taxAmount` are now computed with full floating-point precision. Rounding to 2 decimal places is applied only once at the return statement, applied uniformly to all four output fields including `total`.\n\n**Assessment**: **Correct and well-designed.** This is the standard approach for financial calculations: carry full precision through intermediate steps, then round once at output. The tests at `/workspace/tests/billing.test.ts` (lines 46-59) specifically validate the penny-edge rounding case, which would fail with double-rounding.\n\n**Suggestion (not a bug)**: For production financial code, consider using a decimal arithmetic library or integer-based cent calculations to avoid IEEE 754 floating-point artifacts. For this codebase's scale and precision requirements, the current approach is perfectly adequate.\n\n---\n\n### Fix 4: OrderRepository.update -- Missing Spread of Existing Fields\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/orders/repository.ts`, line 38\n\n**Bug**: The `update()` method used `{ ...updates, id, updatedAt: Date.now() }` which did NOT spread the existing record first. This meant any fields not included in `updates` were silently dropped, effectively replacing the entire order with just the update payload plus `id` and `updatedAt`.\n\n**Fix**: Changed to `{ ...existing, ...updates, id, updatedAt: Date.now() }`.\n\n**Assessment**: **Correct.** Spreading `existing` first, then `updates`, ensures that (a) all original fields are preserved, (b) only the explicitly provided update fields override them, and (c) `id` is never overwritable and `updatedAt` is always refreshed. The test at `/workspace/tests/orders.test.ts` (lines 141-160) directly validates that updating `status` preserves `customerId`, `notes`, `items`, and `total`.\n\n**One observation**: The original planted bug also removed the `...existing` spread but added an explicit `id` field that was not in the original clean code (which had `{ ...existing, ...updates, updatedAt: Date.now() }`). The fix adds back `...existing` but keeps the explicit `id` override. This is a harmless defensive addition -- since `id` is already in `existing` and should never be in `updates`, the explicit `id` is redundant but not harmful. It arguably adds a tiny bit of safety.\n\n---\n\n### Fix 5: InventoryService -- Spurious Status Check Blocking Cancellation Handling\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/inventory/service.ts`, lines 44-49\n\n**Bug**: The `handleOrderCancelled` handler checked `if (eventWithItems.status !== 'cancelled') return;`, but the `OrderCancelledEvent` type (defined in `/workspace/src/events/types.ts`) does not include a `status` field. Furthermore, looking at how `cancelOrder` in `/workspace/src/orders/service.ts` emits the `CANCELLED` event (lines 75-83), it does NOT include a `status` property on the event payload. This meant the status check would always see `undefined !== 'cancelled'` as `true` and return early, so stock was **never** released on cancellation.\n\n**Fix**: Removed the `status` field from the type assertion and removed the guard clause entirely.\n\n**Assessment**: **Correct.** The `ORDER_EVENTS.CANCELLED` event is only emitted when an order is actually being cancelled, so a status check within the handler is both redundant and (in this case) broken. The test at `/workspace/tests/inventory.test.ts` (lines 63-83) validates stock release on cancellation.\n\n**Important note about the test**: The test at `/workspace/tests/inventory.test.ts` line 77 still includes `status: 'cancelled'` in the emitted event payload. This is testing the inventory service directly (not through the order service), and with the fix applied, this extra property is simply ignored since the status guard was removed. The test passes, but it is somewhat misleading -- it suggests the event payload normally contains `status`, which it does not when emitted by `OrderService.cancelOrder()`. This is a minor test hygiene issue, not a correctness bug.\n\n---\n\n### Fix 6: OrderService.refundOrder -- Off-by-One in Refund Window Check\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/orders/service.ts`, line 99\n\n**Bug**: The condition `daysSinceCreation >= REFUND_WINDOW_DAYS` rejected refunds on exactly day 30, even though the business rule (per the constant name `REFUND_WINDOW_DAYS = 30`) implies orders should be refundable within a 30-day window, inclusive of day 30 itself.\n\n**Fix**: Changed `>=` to `>`.\n\n**Assessment**: **Correct.** An order created exactly 30 days ago should still be refundable. The tests at `/workspace/tests/orders.test.ts` (lines 93-104 and 106-116) explicitly test both the boundary (day 30 allowed) and the day-after (day 31 rejected).\n\n**No issues found.**\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| # | File | Bug | Fix Quality | Issues |\n|---|------|-----|-------------|--------|\n| 1 | `src/events/bus.ts` | Global handler registry shared across instances | Correct | None |\n| 2 | `src/billing/service.ts` | Missing `.bind(this)` on refund handler | Correct | None |\n| 3 | `src/billing/calculator.ts` | Double-rounding intermediates + unrounded total | Correct | None |\n| 4 | `src/orders/repository.ts` | `update()` dropped existing fields | Correct | None |\n| 5 | `src/inventory/service.ts` | Spurious status check blocked stock release | Correct | None |\n| 6 | `src/